coeff_comments:
The commercial tests of the two_x0002_stage noncatalytic
process of gas cleaning were performed in a heating
furnace (intended for heating the feed of a vacuum
column) at an oil refinery in Haifa (Israel). The vol_x0002_
ume of flue gases released from the furnace was
25000–30000 m 3/h (NTP). The concentration of
nitrogen oxides in the flue gases (in terms of NO 2 at an
oxygen content to 3 vol %) was 500–550 mg/m 3
(NTP) [(244–268) × 10–4%].
The reducing mixture obtained as a result of the
thermal decomposition of an aqueous solution of urea
was introduced into the high_x0002_temperature zone of the
furnace with a flue gas temperature of 905–960°C.
The above mixture but activated with an additive was
placed in the low_x0002_temperature zone of the furnace with
a flue gas temperature of 410–420°C. As a result of the
two_x0002_stage process of gas cleaning, the concentration of
nitrogen oxides was decreased to 20–35 mg/m3
[(10⎯ 17) × 10 –4%]. Thus, the total efficiency of the
purification of flue gases ejected from the heating fur_x0002_
nace was 94–96% Fig. 2
coeff_tech: Suppression of the formation of nitrogen oxides

coeff_comments:
The commercial tests of the two_x0002_stage noncatalytic
process of gas cleaning were performed in a heating
furnace (intended for heating the feed of a vacuum
column) at an oil refinery in Haifa (Israel). The vol_x0002_
ume of flue gases released from the furnace was
25000–30000 m 3/h (NTP). The concentration of
nitrogen oxides in the flue gases (in terms of NO 2 at an
oxygen content to 3 vol %) was 500–550 mg/m 3
(NTP) [(244–268) × 10–4%].
The reducing mixture obtained as a result of the
thermal decomposition of an aqueous solution of urea
was introduced into the high_x0002_temperature zone of the
furnace with a flue gas temperature of 905–960°C.
The above mixture but activated with an additive was
placed in the low_x0002_temperature zone of the furnace with
a flue gas temperature of 410–420°C. As a result of the
two_x0002_stage process of gas cleaning, the concentration of
nitrogen oxides was decreased to 20–35 mg/m3
[(10⎯ 17) × 10 –4%]. Thus, the total efficiency of the
purification of flue gases ejected from the heating fur_x0002_
nace was 94–96% Fig. 2
coeff_tech: Suppression of the formation of nitrogen oxides

coeff_comments: In this model, energy generation (diesel and fossil fuel combustion) is treated as market activities (e.g. market for diesel, burned in building machine). Therefoe, there's no inventory for CH4 and N2O related to diesel/fossil fuel combustion directly linked to the mineral processing activities. The CH4 and N2O in the inventory is likely to be from tailings, explosives, and/or soil disturbance (for N2O); and release of trapped methane, and organic matter (for CH4). These are mostly negligible (<3% of impacts to climate change, each), and will be ignored for now

coeff_comments:
The commercial tests of the two_x0002_stage noncatalytic
process of gas cleaning were performed in a heating
furnace (intended for heating the feed of a vacuum
column) at an oil refinery in Haifa (Israel). The vol_x0002_
ume of flue gases released from the furnace was
25000–30000 m 3/h (NTP). The concentration of
nitrogen oxides in the flue gases (in terms of NO 2 at an
oxygen content to 3 vol %) was 500–550 mg/m 3
(NTP) [(244–268) × 10–4%].
The reducing mixture obtained as a result of the
thermal decomposition of an aqueous solution of urea
was introduced into the high_x0002_temperature zone of the
furnace with a flue gas temperature of 905–960°C.
The above mixture but activated with an additive was
placed in the low_x0002_temperature zone of the furnace with
a flue gas temperature of 410–420°C. As a result of the
two_x0002_stage process of gas cleaning, the concentration of
nitrogen oxides was decreased to 20–35 mg/m3
[(10⎯ 17) × 10 –4%]. Thus, the total efficiency of the
purification of flue gases ejected from the heating fur_x0002_
nace was 94–96% Fig. 2
coeff_tech: Suppression of the formation of nitrogen oxides
